<TEXT>
sports entrepreneur george shinn said 
friday he is withdrawing his bid for ptl because he could not 
compete with a canadian companys 113 million offer for the 
2200acre christian retreat and theme park 
based upon our evaluation of the ptl property as of today and 
our desired uses we cannot compete with the offer currently on the 
table shinn said in a statement 
shinn majority owner of the new charlotte hornets of the 
national basketball association and the charlotte knights 
minorleague baseball team originally offered 75 million for 
ptls assets including 25 million in cash 
ptl trustee mc red benton said on wednesday that the 
leading bidder for ptl was canadian real estate magnate peter 
thomas representing samoth capital corp 
benton said he expected by sept 1 to have a firm offer from 
thomas for the heritage usa theme park television network and 
other property near fort mill sc 
we have expressed to mr benton and mr thomas our best wishes 
for a prompt and successful completion of their proposed sale 
shinn said 
ptl with debts of up to 130 million has been reorganizing in 
us bankruptcy court since june 1987 three months after founder 
jim bakker resigned amid a sexandmoney scandal 
bakker also wants to buy ptls assets and said two weeks ago 
that he was prepared to pay at least 77 million in cash 
immediately by comparison thomas has offered to pay 46 million 
in cash and finance the rest of the purchase price over five years 
asked whether he thinks shinns dropping out improves bakkers 
chances bakker attorney ryan hovis said i dont think it makes 
any difference 
