the afternoon 
diplomatic sources said both sides set forth their often 
divergent positions on numerous intractable subjects from the 
border dispute to exchange of prisoners 
velayati gave the first public indication of a problem when he 
told reporters after the morning session that a settlement requires 
observance of the 1975 algiers treaty 
the treaty made the southern boundary between iran and iraq the 
middle of the shattalarab waterway and granted iran its claim to 
the eastern half the waterway is iraqs only access to the sea at 
the persian gulf 
in 1980 president saddam hussein of iraq repudiated the treaty 
five days later on sept 22 the iraqi army invaded iran 
iran says the treaty still is valid under international law 
the treaty is a crucial issue in the peace talks because a un 
peace resolution calls for a troop withdrawal to internationally 
recognized boundaries 
iraq says the boundaries are in dispute and seeks renegotiation 
of them 
sources close to the iranian delegation said the iraqi side was 
insisting the ceasefire line be drawn so as to give iraq control 
of the waterway 
the sources speaking on condition of anonymity said iraq also 
was pressing for early dredging by the united nations of the 
waterway heavily silted after eight years of war and impassable 
because of sunken ships 
neither velayati nor aziz spoke to reporters after the session 
friday night 
