<TEXT>
an unusual moderate earthquake hit 
in the northern atlantic ocean off the coast of bermuda today 
officials at the united states geological survey said 
a moderate earthquake centered in the ocean about 80 miles 
west of hamilton bermuda struck at 305 am edt said usgs 
spokeswoman pat jorgenson 
the quake measured 53 on the richter scale jorgenson said but 
she said the usgs has not issued a tidal warning in connection with 
the earthquake 
it was felt strongly by the residents of hamilton she added 
the richter scale is an openended gauge of energy released by 
an earthquake as measured by ground motion recorded on a 
seismograph every increase of one number means that the ground 
motion is 10 times greater 
a quake with a magnitude of 4 can cause moderate damage in a 
populated area a quake of magnitude 5 considerable damage a 
magnitude 6 quake severe damage one of magnitude 7 widespread 
heavy damage and a magnitude 8 quake a great earthquake 
capable of tremendous damage 
the usgs said todays earthquake struck in the same area where 
another quake hit last june 24 but it is unusual for a quake to 
hit in the north atlantic we have them in the southern pacific all 
the time said one usgs official 
there was no information immediately available about damages or 
injuries officials said 
</TEXT>
