<TEXT>
what worried george bush and his top aides 
most as he and dan quayle prepared for their first news conference 
was how to deal with questions about their differences on issues 
the indiana senators national guard service and his brief 
encounter with paula parkinson were secondary concerns at best 
when bush aides asked quayle why he joined the indiana national 
guard in 1969 he replied that he wanted to go to law school had 
he been drafted he already had passed his preinduction physical 
his law school plans would have been delayed three years 
never mentioned was the suggestion that he might have joined the 
national guard during that period to avoid service in vietnam 
neither was quayle asked if his prominent family had helped him 
get into the guard he didnt volunteer the information that a call 
was made on his behalf 
the briefing session took place in a suite on the 40th floor of 
the new orleans marriott hotel it was the second day of the 
republican national convention and bush had just made public the 
biggest news of the week his choice of a running mate 
a dynamic young leader for the future was how bush 
introduced his choice at a rally on a mississippi river levee 
within 24 hours of its disclosure that decision generated a 
flood of unfavorable publicity that threatened to undermine the 
benefits expected from a carefully scripted convention damage 
control became the top priority in the bush campaign 
after nearly two weeks bush remains in danger of having his 
message overshadowed by the persistent questions about his running 
mate 
how much influence did quayles family exert to get him into the 
national guard did he require similar help to get into law school 
did his relationship with parkinson ever go beyond the most casual 
encounter during a golf weekend in florida 
how bush came to choose one of the most obscure people on his 
list of potential vice presidents and how his staff dealt with the 
controversy remains a wellkept secret 
but interviews with people who had varying degrees of 
familiarity with the process produced some details of the process 
all of the people interviewed insisted on anonymity 
bush held off his search for a running mate until after the 
democratic ticket of michael dukakis and lloyd bentsen was set in 
midjuly 
the idea was that bush would have the advantage of countering 
whatever vice presidential strategy dukakis pursued 
the list of those under consideration was long two opponents 
for the presidential nomination senate gop leader bob dole of 
kansas and rep jack kemp of new york one close friend sen alan 
simpson of wyoming two other senators pete domenici of new mexico 
and quayle two women former transportation secretary elizabeth 
dole and and sen nancy kassebaum of kansas govs george 
deukmejian of california jim thompson of illinois carroll 
campbell of south carolina and john sununu of new hampshire and 
former gov richard thornburgh of pennsylvania 
bush sought advice from a wide range of people but never gave a 
hint of whether he was leaning toward one or another individual 
for the most part he listened and took notes on yellow pads 
as the time for the republican convention grew near bush held 
two meetings in his office in the old executive office building 
with top advisers to discuss the contenders 
the participants included treasury secretary james a baker iii 
slated to become campaign chairman pollster robert teeter 
campaign manager lee atwater staff chief craig fuller media 
adviser roger ailes and friend and adviser nicholas brady who 
would succeed baker at treasury 
the first meeting was held aug 8 the second one week later 
by the end of the second meeting the list of prospects had been 
pared to no more than eight names still on it were both doles 
simpson domenici quayle kemp and thornburgh there also were 
rumors of an unnamed wild card 
atwater and teeter were strong advocates of a generational 
approach the choice of a socalled babyboomer that 
description is given to americans born between 1946 and 1964 
people coming to political maturity in this election they are 
voters who grew up in the age of television whose views of 
government were shaped by vietnam and watergate and whose lives 
were touched by rapidly changing attitudes toward drugs and sex 
both quayle 41 and kemp 50 were felt to represent a positive 
generational contrast to the 67yearold bentsen 
that argument appealed to bush and as he looked at the two men 
he was far more comfortable with quayle than with kemp 
bush kept his decision a secret until he landed at belle chasse 
naval air station outside new orleans on the morning of the second 
day of the gop convention 
he had a brief symbolic meeting with president reagan on the 
runway and whispered to him that he had decided on quayle 
a moment later he gave top aides the news and began to call the 
other people on the list 
methodically bush went down his list saving quayle for last 
the indiana senator appeared with bush at a riverside rally where 
an enthusiastic bush called his running mate a dynamic young 
leader for the future 
conservatives were ecstatic quayle was one of their own a hawk 
who voted the conservative line on social and economic issues 
in fact it was quayles conservative views that bush aides 
assumed would be the subject of most questions at the introductory 
wednesday morning news conference 
the indiana senator is a stronger advocate of the earliest 
possible deployment of the star wars missile defense system than 
either bush or reagan and also was far more skeptical of the recent 
arms control treaty between the us and the soviet union 
he also differed with the administration on some labor issues 
including legislation to ban use of lie detectors to screen job 
applicants the administration supported the ban quayle opposed it 
as for paula parkinson the insurance industry lobbyist and 
playboy model quayle and the campaign advisers dismissed her as an 
old story parkinson made headlines in 1981 when it was disclosed 
she had shared a room in a florida condominium with rep tom evans 
rdel quayle and rep tom railsback rill also stayed at the 
condominium but denied any involvement with parkinson 
the national guard service was viewed as no different than what 
millions of other americans had done at the time 
twelve hours later they learned how wrong they were 
it was the national guard story and parkinson that made 
headlines 
