<TEXT>
michael dukakis joined thousands saturday to 
mark the 25th anniversary of martin luther king jrs march on 
washington and promised to pursue the slain civil rights leaders 
famous dream if elected president 
we must march until we reach the finish line at the top of the 
hill and there we will find no barriers separating us one from the 
other dukakis told a rally at the lincoln memorial after the 
anniversary march 
there we will merge the reality of america with the promise 
of america he said there together together we will fulfill 
the american dream 
dukakis and his wife kitty marched from the washington 
monument to the lincoln memorial in a row of dignitaries that 
included kings widow coretta scott king jesse jackson dukakiss 
former rival in the democratic presidential race naacp executive 
director benjamin hooks the rev joseph lowery and atlanta mayor 
andrew young 
dukakis saluted mrs king and his former rival referring to 
jackson as a man able to lift the hopes and spirits of millions 
of americans with the energy and vision and the excitement of his 
campaign dr king must be very proud of jesse jackson 
dukakis was wellreceived by the gathering and there were chants 
of where is george after dukakis completed his speech 
he also took time before the speech to meet with representatives 
of several black media outlets promising to bring more jackson 
supporters into his campaign and to campaign hard for the black 
vote 
jackson who did not speak until after dukakis had departed did 
not mention the democratic presidential ticket specifically 
but he urged his followers to vote and it was clear it did not 
mean for them to vote for the republican ticket 
george bush is not in washington today he said he must 
not be here for the inauguration next january 
in rhetoric unlike any dukakis had delivered previously to a 
predominantly black audience the massachusetts governor likened 
king to lincoln using uncharacteristically emotional language in 
his tribute 
like the man whose memorial we gather at today martin luther 
king jr changed the course of history dukakis said and as 
abraham lincoln in his time defined our nations course at 
gettysburg so dr king in his time defined americas soul 
dukakis continued the dream he shared with us that afternoon 
25 years ago was more powerful than any single cause it soared 
above all barriers of race and creed and it has endured and 
expanded through time because it was born of a profound optimism 
about life it was nurtured by faith in the promise of america it 
was sustained by his belief that we americans for all our 
wonderful diversity and it is a wonderful diversity are one 
people one nation one community 
dukakis recalled racial beatings and bombings and the 
assassination of president kennedy that occurred the same year of 
kings march and said that while much progress toward the 
realization of kings dream has been made that much more needs to 
be done to deliver america from the scourge of racism and the 
slow death of indifference 
we cannot be satisfied to rest here dukakis said in quoting 
kennedy this is the side of the hill not the top we have 
made a beginning but we have only begun 
the democratic nominee promised to lead a nation that will 
march on to fulfill kings call for racial harmony 
dukakis without directly mentioning the reagan administration 
said a litany of problems facing minority americans have not been 
addressed including discrimination a lack of fair housing and 
affordable health care poor schools high teenage pregnancy rates 
and infant mortality and shoddy enforcement of civil and voting 
rights laws 
he applauded bush for supporting antidiscrimination laws to 
protect aids victims but also left little doubt about his 
perception of the reagan administrations record on issues of 
concern to minority americans 
we must march until we have a united states department of 
justice that understands the meaning of the word justice he 
said we must march until we have a civil rights commission that 
believes in civil rights my friends we must march until we have a 
president who understands and respects the constitution of the 
united states 
dukakis ended his speech with a rhetorical flourish more likely 
to come from jackson than dukakis 
let us in the words of dr king transform the jangling 
discords of our nation into a beautiful symphony of brotherhood 
dukakis said let us look up let us march on and little by 
little step by step hand in hand together we will overcome 
