<TEXT>
a soviet diplomat said saturday that he was 
optimistic a quick agreement could be reached between china and the 
soviet union on the conflict in cambodia 
soviet deputy foreign minister igor rogachev arrived in the 
chinese capital for talks set to begin sunday asked by reporters 
at the airport if a breakthrough was imminent rogachev said i 
think so 
his chinese counterpart deputy foreign minister tian zengpei 
was more cautious saying only we hope to make some headway 
the two nations broke off relations in the early 1960s over 
ideological and strategic differences normalization talks opened 
in 1982 but they bogged down over three major obstacles moscows 
support of vietnams nineyear occupation of cambodia soviet 
troops in afghanistan and soviet forces stationed along the 
chinese border 
with the soviet pullout from afghanistan and a reduction of 
forces along the border cambodia could be the last obstacle to 
normalizing relations 
if the conflict there is resolved it could also pave the way 
for a summit meeting between soviet leader mikhail gorbachev and 
chinese leader deng xiaoping 
the communist giants have not held a summit in 30 years 
we see some light at the end of the tunnel rogachev said of 
the cambodia talks 
rogachev said he expected the talks to last about a week it 
will be the first time the two sides have met solely to discuss 
cambodia 
rogachev he did not reveal what was on the agenda for the talks 
which are closed to foreign reporters 
we are waiting for initiatives from the kampuchean cambodian 
side we with our chinese colleagues can only facilitate or 
assist in the settlement he said 
he also said a final solution would have to await the outcome of 
a meeting in november between cambodan resistance leader norodom 
sihanouk and hun sen prime minister of the hanoibacked government 
in cambodia 
china has said it wants the soviet union to put pressure on 
vietnam to completely pull out of cambodia as soon as possible 
vietnam which invaded cambodia in 1978 has agreed to withdraw 
50000 troops about half its forces there this year and all its 
troops by 1990 
in the past china has backed the communist khmer rouge rebel 
faction in cambodia it now supports a fourparty coalition 
government made up of the three resistance groups including the 
khmer rouge and hun sens forces the government would be headed 
by former national leader sihanouk who remains probably the most 
popular political figure in cambodia 
